Pitt Athletics

Project Summary

The project that I selected is the Pitt Athletics data set. The data set contains real, anonymous information from University of Pittsburgh football season ticket holders (STH). Information about the season ticket holders included:

  • Age
  • Gender
  • Distance and direction from Acrisure Stadium
  • Drive times to Acrisure Stadium
  • Month and Day of the Week tickets were purchased
  • Ticket price type
  • Ticket price level
  • Number of tickets
  • Price per ticket
  • Whether or not the STH renewed their tickets for the following year

The problem associated with this data set was to formulate a data model that would predict whether or not a future STH would renew their season tickets based on the information provided above.

This problem is a classification problem. The objective was to correctly classify individuals into one of two categories: Non-Event/0 (Did/will not renew season tickets) or Event/1 (Did/will renew season tickets)

In order to find the best number of clustersm we will use a kneebend plot

In[26]:
tots_within = []

K = range(1, 31)

for k in K:
    km = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=121, n_init=25, max_iter=500)
    km = km.fit( X )
    
    tots_within.append( km.inertia_ )

fig, ax = plt.subplots()

ax.plot( K, tots_within, 'bo-' )
ax.set_xlabel('number of clusters')
ax.set_ylabel('total within sum of squares')

plt.show()

Based on this plot, I chose to use 6 as my number of clusters. 7 could have also been used, which would have lined up with the number of price_level value counts. 6 does line up with purchase_dow

In[27]:

Modeling

Here are the details of the formula I found to provide the best results as a model:

In[28]:
best_model = 'y ~ (miles_log + price_per_ticket)**2 + np.power(miles_log, 2) + np.power(price_per_ticket, 2) * (gender_known + bin_age + direction + purchase_month + purchase_dow + price_type + price_level + lump_ticket_count)'
In[29]:
best_fit = smf.logit(formula= best_model, data = pitt_df_clean).fit()

Optimization terminated successfully.
         Current function value: 0.450918
         Iterations 8
In[30]:
def fit_and_assess_logistic(mod_name, a_formula, train_data, threshold):
    a_mod = smf.logit(formula=a_formula, data=train_data).fit()
    
    train_copy = train_data.copy()
    
    train_copy['pred_probability'] = a_mod.predict( train_data )
    
    train_copy['pred_class'] = np.where( train_copy.pred_probability > threshold, 1, 0 )
    
    TN, FP, FN, TP = confusion_matrix( train_copy.y.to_numpy(), train_copy.pred_class.to_numpy() ).ravel()
    
    Accuracy = (TN + TP) / (TN + FP + FN + TP)
    
    Sensitivity = (TP) / (TP + FN)
    
    Specificity = (TN) / (TN + FP)
    
    FPR = 1 - Specificity
    
    ROC_AUC = roc_auc_score( train_copy.y.to_numpy(), train_copy.pred_probability.to_numpy() )
    
    res_dict = {'model_name': mod_name,
                'model_formula': a_formula,
                'num_coefs': len( a_mod.params ),
                'threshold': threshold,
                'Accuracy': Accuracy,
                'Sensitivity': Sensitivity,
                'Specificity': Specificity,
                'FPR': FPR,
                'ROC_AUC': ROC_AUC}
    
    return pd.DataFrame( res_dict, index=[0] )

In[34]:
def my_coefplot(mod, figsize_use=(10,14)):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = figsize_use)
    
    ax.errorbar( y=mod.params.index,
                 x=mod.params,
                 xerr = 2 * mod.bse,
                 fmt='o', color='k', ecolor='k', elinewidth=2, ms=10)
    
    ax.axvline(x=0, linestyle='--', linewidth=3.5, color='grey')
    
    ax.set_xlabel('coefficient value')
    
    plt.show()

Concluding Analysis

Based on the model that I formulated, I believe we can derive that the following variables play a key factor in whether or not a STH is likely to renew their tickets:

  • knowing the gender of the STH
  • the distance driven to the stadium
  • the price level of the tickets

The other issue is that this dataset had missings to deal with, and since KMeans can't process missings, it limited the value it could bring to the analysis
